# Quest List — Progression (Unlock) Sort Order PRD

## Overview

- **Status**: Planning
- **Created**: 2026-07-02
- **Updated**: 2026-07-02
- **Owner**: josephjang
- **Translations**: Korean companion at `feature-quest-unlock-sort.ko.prd` (kept in sync 1:1)
- **Wording convention**: this English PRD describes orderings in English and uses full language
  names (English / Korean / Japanese). This PRD is **implementation-independent** — it states the
  required behavior, not how it is coded.

## Problem Statement

In the Quest page, the task list is ordered alphabetically by the English task name and is never
re-ordered. Alphabetical order conveys no sense of progression — a player cannot see which tasks come
first or what unlocks what — and in Korean/Japanese it is doubly unhelpful because the order still
follows the English names.

An investigation of the in-game **Tasks tab** showed its order is **reverse unlock-time** (the most
recently unlocked task appears on top) — a dynamic, per-player order. The app **cannot and should not**
reproduce it (see Non-Goals): it records no unlock timestamp, and a time-based order would reshuffle on
every manual edit.

Instead the app should present a **stable forward progression order**: each task appears after the
tasks required to unlock it. Because this is driven by prerequisite relationships, it is **identical in
every language** and **independent of the player's progress**.

## Goals

- [ ] Goal 1: The quest list is ordered by **forward progression** — a task always appears after all of
      the tasks required to unlock it.
- [ ] Goal 2: The list stays a **flat list** (no trader grouping or group headers).
- [ ] Goal 3: The order is **static** — independent of the player's completion state and of the active
      UI language. Switching language re-localizes the row text only; it does not reorder.
- [ ] Goal 4: The ordering behavior is protected by an automated guard so it cannot silently regress.

## Non-Goals (Scope Out)

- **Reproducing the in-game Tasks-tab order.** That order is reverse unlock-time — dynamic and
  per-player. The app stores no unlock/activation timestamp (quest progress records only status and a
  last-edited time, and not-yet-done tasks are computed, not stored), and a time-based order would churn
  on every manual edit. Fidelity to the game's exact order is therefore explicitly out of scope.
- Recording unlock/activation timestamps.
- Trader grouping or group headers.
- Database schema or data changes.
- User-selectable sort criteria (e.g. sort by trader / status / progress like the in-game columns).
  Deferred to a future iteration.
- Alphabetical-by-localized-name ordering (that was the hideout solution; it does not apply here).

## Requirements / Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] R1 (prerequisite order): For any task T, every prerequisite of T appears **before** T in the list.
- [ ] R2 (language-invariant): The list order is identical in English, Korean, and Japanese; only the
      displayed text differs per language.
- [ ] R3 (progress-invariant): Completing or resetting a task does not reorder the list. Within an
      active filter, the remaining tasks keep their progression order.
- [ ] R4 (deterministic parallel order): Two tasks with no prerequisite relationship between them are
      ordered by a **stable, deterministic** rule. (The rule need not match the game — see Non-Goals.)

## Constraints & Known Limitation

The game's Tasks-tab order (reverse unlock-time) is dynamic and per-player and is **not reproducible**
from the app's data — there is no unlock timestamp, and a time-based order would be unstable under
manual editing. Matching the game's exact order is therefore out of scope; the target is a **stable,
useful progression order** derived from prerequisite relationships.

Prerequisite relationships are the source of truth for ordering. Level-requirement data in the dataset
is **sparse/unreliable** (most tasks carry no stored level), so ordering must not depend on it.

## Design Decisions (requirements-level)

| Decision | Rationale | Date |
|----------|-----------|------|
| Forward progression order (not reversed) | "Do this, then this" is more useful for a planning tool; a reversed order would show later parts (e.g. Part 3) above earlier ones (Part 1) | 2026-07-02 |
| Do not reproduce the in-game order | It is reverse unlock-time — dynamic, per-player, not recorded, and would churn on manual edits | 2026-07-02 |
| Static, language-independent order | Prerequisite-driven order is stable across progress and language | 2026-07-02 |
| Flat list, not trader-grouped | Keeps the current list UI; grouping is out of scope | 2026-07-02 |
| Ordering does not use level requirements | Level data in the dataset is sparse/unreliable | 2026-07-02 |

## Verification

- [ ] Manual: a multi-part chain appears in order (e.g. Part 1 → Part 2 → Part 3); prerequisites appear
      above the tasks they unlock.
- [ ] Manual: completing/resetting tasks does not reorder the list; the order is stable.
- [ ] Manual: switching English / Korean / Japanese re-localizes text but does **not** reorder.
- [ ] Automated: a guard test asserts the prerequisite-before-task invariant and deterministic output.

